message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. PSA is a protein produced by the prostate gland and is involved in the liquefaction of semen. It is not involved in sperm production, maintaining the corpus luteum, or regulation of transcription factors and phosphorylation of proteins.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. PSA (prostate-specific antigen) is an enzyme produced by the prostate gland, and its main physiological function is to liquefy semen to allow for sperm motility. It is used as a screening tool for prostate cancer, BPH, and prostatitis. None of the other options are related to the function of PSA. Sperm production is mainly regulated by follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH). The corpus luteum is maintained by luteinizing hormone (LH) after ovulation, and regulation of transcription factors and phosphorylation of proteins is a broad biological process that involves a wide range of enzymes and signaling pathways.

Sperm production is not directly related to PSA, and the other options are not functions of PSA.

PSA is a protease enzyme that cleaves semenogelin I and semenogelin II, which contribute to the viscosity of semen, resulting in the liquefaction of semen after ejaculation.
